You could do both here, as a notification.  Have these two ``if``s independent and do a notify of either, both, or none.  And then after that, check both before allowing it.  feels a little redundant, I know, but those checks are pretty fast, I think.  And nice to get both errors out there if both exist.  I really hate that feeling of fixing one thing, try again, fail again, fix another thing....  

Something like:

    if (!$scope.user.loggedin) {
        thNotify...
    }
    if (!$scope.canSaveClassifications()) {
        thNotify...
    }
    if ($scope.canSaveClassifications() && $scope.user.loggedin) {
        save it...
    }

 [python 3.5](https://docs.python.org/3.5/library/urllib.parse.html#urllib.parse.urlsplit) says: port is None when value if not valid. and the new  `_encode_netloc()`:

```py
def _encode_netloc(parts):
	try:
		hostname = to_unicode(parts.hostname.encode('idna'))
		netloc = hostname if parts.port is None else '%s:%s' % (hostname, parts.port)
	except UnicodeError:
		netloc = parts.netloc
	return netloc
```

